# R usually guesses well what type of plot to use if data is coded correctly
plot(dat$General_Party)

# enlarge this plot in your RStudio window to see all categories properly.

plot(factor(dat$General_Party[dat$General_Party!="Nonpartisan"]))

# boxplots have formulas, usually y ~ x is the sturcture everywhere

boxplot(dat$total[dat$total>=500 & dat$total<=10750] ~ dat$General_Party[dat$total>=500 & dat$total<=10750])

table(dat$General_Party[dat$Status_of_Candidate=="Lost" | dat$Status_of_Candidate=="Won"],
      dat$Status_of_Candidate[dat$Status_of_Candidate=="Lost" | dat$Status_of_Candidate=="Won"])
##              
##               Default Winner Lost Withdrew  Won
##   Democratic               0 1898        0 1827
##   Nonpartisan              0 3677        0 3395
##   Republican               0  524        0  178
##   Third-Party              0  481        0  139
##   Unknown                  0   19        0   17
party <- dat$General_Party
party[party=="Nonpartisan"] <- NA # NA is r's way of registering missing data, without quotation marks
party[party=="Third-Party"] <- NA
party[party=="Unknown"] <- NA

party <- factor(party) # getting rid of empty factor levels by replacing the old objects by the new one

status <- dat$Status_of_Candidate
status[status=="Default Winner"] <- NA
status[status=="Withdrew"] <- NA
status <- factor(status)

table(party,status) # let's pretend the research question is whether 
##             status
## party        Lost  Won
##   Democratic 1898 1827
##   Republican  524  178
# republicans are more likely to lose than democrats


prop.table(table(party,status))
##             status
## party              Lost        Won
##   Democratic 0.42873278 0.41269483
##   Republican 0.11836458 0.04020782
chisq.test(table(party,status))
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  table(party, status)
## X-squared = 132.84, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
party2 <- party
party2[party=="Republican"] <- NA
party2 <- factor(party2)

total <- dat$total

mean(total[party2=="Democratic" & status=="Won"],na.rm=T)
## [1] 36824.7
mean(total[party2=="Democratic" & status=="Lost"],na.rm=T)
## [1] 39260.9
t.test(total[party2=="Democratic"] ~ status[party2=="Democratic"])
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  total[party2 == "Democratic"] by status[party2 == "Democratic"]
## t = 0.24898, df = 3494.9, p-value = 0.8034
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -16748.15  21620.56
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Lost  mean in group Won 
##            39260.9            36824.7
